                     <handNote xml:id="h2" script="Ethiopic">The handwriting appears irregular and uneven, mostly due to irregular ruling (c.p. fols. 6v, 7r), different size of columns (c.p. fols. 5r, 6v, 7r, 98r), different size of the letters (c.p. fol. 51rc). <!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h3" script="Ethiopic">
The scribe tends to small, broad, rounded, broadly spaced letters.<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h4" script="Ethiopic">
Loops of the vowel markers tend to be open.<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h5" script="Ethiopic">
Particular features are: <!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h6" script="Ethiopic">
- the form of 'one' (፩) is rounded at the bottom and upwards-oriented (e.g.: fol. 5vb l.1).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h7" script="Ethiopic">
- the horizontal strokes containing the numbers are constituted by dots (eg. fols. 97vc l.2, 107ra l.19), or by the combination of dots and stroke (eg. fols. 4va l.10, 100va l.1)  <!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h8" script="Ethiopic">
- the letter ሐ often has an unusually long hairline stroke at the top (eg. fols. 7rb l.19, 10va  l.12)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h9" script="Ethiopic">
- the loops of ቶ and ቆ are placed on the left side of the horizontal stroke, not in the middle,<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h10" script="Ethiopic">
mostly connected to the left stroke instead of being connected the upper horizontal stroke (eg. for ቶ: fols. 6rb l.4, 7va l.11, 9va l.1; eg. for ቆ: fols. 4rb l.1, 4rc l.1).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                     <handNote xml:id="h11" script="Ethiopic">
- the word ʾƎgziʾabǝḥer is in the most cases written with a ligature.<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></handNote>
                  </handDesc>
